{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476507"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:48:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:48:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13771"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13771"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.08,0.24,0.12,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6390"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67237"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6390"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13771"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52689"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1228"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"3049"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12495"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22069"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42924"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44174"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67237"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department by ambulance after taking an intentional overdose of methylphenidate (Ritalin) 40 mg tablets. He has a medical history of attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) but no other significant medical history. He does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears agitated with a heart rate of 140/min, blood pressure 180/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, temperature 37.2\u00b0C, and SpO2 99% on room air. His pupils are dilated but neurological examination is otherwise normal. An ECG shows sinus tachycardia with non-specific ST segment changes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment for his cardiovascular instability?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metoprolol","Amiodarone","Diazepam","Adenosine","Phentolamine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has features of methylphenidate toxicity including agitation, tachycardia, hypertension and ECG changes. Methylphenidate is a stimulant medication that inhibits reuptake of dopamine and noradrenaline. \u003Cstrong\u003EDiazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment as benzodiazepines reduce CNS stimulation and help control agitation, hypertension and tachycardia through GABA-mediated inhibition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E, while potentially useful in specific circumstances, requires careful consideration in stimulant toxicity. Beta-blockers can block beta-2 receptors that normally cause vasodilation, potentially leaving alpha-adrenergic effects (vasoconstriction) unopposed. However, beta-1 selective agents like metoprolol may be considered for specific indications such as acute coronary syndrome or refractory tachyarrhythmias, preferably after initial benzodiazepine therapy and with careful monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhentolamine\u003C/strong\u003E, a pure alpha-blocker, can be considered as a second-line agent for refractory hypertension if benzodiazepines are ineffective. Combined alpha/beta blockers like labetalol may be safer than pure beta-blockers if adrenergic blockade is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eadenosine\u003C/strong\u003E are antiarrhythmic drugs used for supraventricular tachycardia but do not address the underlying sympathomimetic toxidrome. The sinus tachycardia here is a manifestation of stimulant toxicity rather than a primary arrhythmia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe overall approach should focus on controlling agitation with benzodiazepines first, which often improves cardiovascular parameters. Additional interventions can then be considered based on specific complications and response to initial therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Methylphenidate toxicity presents with sympathomimetic features including agitation, tachycardia, hypertension and ECG changes.","Benzodiazepines are first-line treatment for methylphenidate toxicity as they address both cardiovascular and neurological manifestations.","Beta-blockers should be used cautiously in stimulant toxicity due to the risk of unopposed alpha effects, though beta-1 selective agents may be considered in specific circumstances."],"references":["Becker WC. Prescription drug misuse: Epidemiology, prevention, identification, and management. In: UpToDate [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/prescription-drug-misuse-epidemiology-prevention-identification-and-management","Scharman EJ, Erdman AR, Cobaugh DJ, Olson KR, Woolf AD, Caravati EM, et al. Methylphenidate poisoning: an evidence-based consensus guideline for out-of-hospital management. Clin Toxicol (Phila). 2007;45(7):737-52. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18058301/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52689"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13771"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52689"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T09:42:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T09:44:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6390"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67237"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d